		<title>Facebook: How to make sure your fans read your posts</title>
		<link>http://tipsandtech.com/facebook-how-to-make-sure-your-fans-read-your-posts/</link>
		<comments>http://tipsandtech.com/facebook-how-to-make-sure-your-fans-read-your-posts/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 01 Apr 2011 16:22:01 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>John</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Facebook]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[EdgeRank]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://tipsandtech.com/?p=270</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[A friend of mine emailed me this morning with a question that has inspired this quick post. Q. John, Can you help me?  I have posted messages to my company Facebook page, but I don&#8217;t think it is going to my fan&#8217;s walls.  Why don&#8217;t they get my posts? A. My understanding is this is [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p><a href="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/images.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-271" title="images" src="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/images.jpg" alt="" width="209" height="241" /></a>A friend of mine emailed me this morning with a question that has inspired this quick post.</p>
<p>Q. John, Can you help me?  I have posted messages to my company Facebook page, but I don&#8217;t think it is going to my fan&#8217;s walls.  Why don&#8217;t they get my posts?</p>
<p>A. My understanding is this is caused by a Facebook algorithm called EdgeRank.</p>
<p>When you (or your friends or fans) login to Facebook, the middle section of the page contains your News Feed.  This is where you can see the information and news that your friend took the time to post to Facebook in hopes that you care enough to read it.  BUT&#8230; did you know, that this news feed does not contain EVERYTHING your friends post to Facebook?  If you look at the very top of your news feed, you will see two options, one says &#8220;Top News&#8221; and the other says &#8220;Most Recent.&#8221;  Facebook, by default, loads the &#8220;Top News&#8221; from your friends when you first login to Facebook.</p>
<p>Your &#8220;Top News&#8221; is where EdgeRank comes in.  EdgeRank rates your friends&#8217; posts and will only post the most popular stories, photos, videos and links to your &#8220;Top News&#8221; news feed.  How it ranks these is not black and white, but it does give more credit to photos and videos and to status updates that generated lots of interaction.  This interaction is defined by the number of &#8220;Likes&#8221; and the number of Comments the post has generated.</p>
<p>Do you ever wonder why stories from yesterday or even a few days ago are showing up on your newsfeed?  That is EdgeRank, those stories are ranking high and if you look, I&#8217;ll bet those stories had good interaction.</p>
<p>If you want to ensure your post is read by more people, make sure you encourage comments and likes in your status updates!  Ask open ended questions, tell people to Like your status, tell your friends and family to like your stuff when they see you post.  The more interaction you get, the more eyes will see it.</p>
<p>If you want to get more out of Facebook and read all the posts from your friends, you simply have to click the &#8220;Most Recent&#8221; button at the top!  And  as a bonus, by clicking on the arrow next to the &#8220;Most Recent&#8221; button, you can pick and choose which group of friends posts you want to read through.  That is, if you have your friends separated into groups. <img src='http://tipsandtech.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt=':)' class='wp-smiley' /> </p>
]]></content:encoded>
