		<title>Easily transfer large files with DROPitTOme</title>
		<link>http://tipsandtech.com/easily-transfer-large-files-with-dropittome/</link>
		<comments>http://tipsandtech.com/easily-transfer-large-files-with-dropittome/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 10 Dec 2010 13:55:30 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>John</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Time Saving Tool]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[DROPitTOme]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[file sharing]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://tipsandtech.com/?p=140</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Yesterday we talked about DropBox and how you can store files in one centralized location and access or share the files from anywhere.  Today we are going to check out another tool that integrates with Dropbox called DropItTo.Me. When you first visit, you will be required to create a new login and password by clicking [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><p><a href="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/dropittome.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-164" title="dropittome" src="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/dropittome.jpg" alt="" width="146" height="32" /></a>Yesterday <a href="http://tipsandtech.com/store-files-online-and-access-them-from-any-computer-with-dropbox/" target="_blank">we talked about DropBox</a> and how you can store files in one centralized location and access or share the files from anywhere.  Today we are going to check out another tool that integrates with Dropbox called <a href="http://dropitto.me" target="_blank">DropItTo.Me</a>.</p>
<p>When you first visit, you will be required to create a new login and password by clicking the &#8220;Resister&#8221; button.  When you register, you will have to create an &#8220;upload&#8221; password.  We&#8217;ll get to this in a minute, first let talk about what this cool tool can do for you.</p>
<p>Have you ever had someone try to email you a file that never was delivered.  Some email services put limits on the file sizes they will allow to be delivered.  If a file that is too large tries to come through, your email service will reject it and sometimes not even tell the sender the email bounced and why.  This is where DropItTo.Me comes in.  It gives you your very own upload link on the internet for you to share with the person sending you the large file(s).  Mine is <a href="http://dropitto.me/jringo" target="_blank">DropItTo.Me/jringo</a> and looks like the image below.</p>
<p><a href="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/12-9-2010-4-12-24-PM.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-166 alignnone" title="12-9-2010 4-12-24 PM" src="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/12-9-2010-4-12-24-PM.png" alt="" width="591" height="252" /></a></p>
<p>This is where the &#8220;upload&#8221; password comes in.  First you share your personal DropItTo.Me url with them and then give them your &#8220;upload&#8221; password.  they simple visit the url, enter the password.  They then see a screen like this.</p>
<p><a href="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/12-9-2010-4-17-20-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-167" title="12-9-2010 4-17-20 PM" src="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/12-9-2010-4-17-20-PM.png" alt="" width="582" height="244" /></a></p>
<p>Your sender can then upload files to you one at a time.</p>
<p>But where do the files go you may ask?  This is where Dropbox comes in. <img src='http://tipsandtech.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt=':)' class='wp-smiley' /> </p>
<p>When you register for your DropItTo.Me account, it integrates with your Dropbox account and automatically creates a folder called DropItToMe <a href="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/12-9-2010-4-18-55-PM.png"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-168" title="12-9-2010 4-18-55 PM" src="http://tipsandtech.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/12-9-2010-4-18-55-PM.png" alt="" width="92" height="125" /></a> in your Dropbox folder.  You can then access the files from any of your Dropbox locations.</p>
<p>Sharing big files has never been easier and this is just plain cool right?  Let me know in the comments below if you have used this and how it has worked for you.</p>
<p><em>On a side note: I want to warn you to be aware who you share your url and upload password with.  These files do go directly to your computer, so don&#8217;t share this info with anyone you don&#8217;t trust.  An evildoer could easily upload a virus that could destroy all the data on your hard drive.</em></p>
]]></content:encoded>
